1
00:00:14,430 --> 00:00:15,430
Um...

2
00:00:15,750 --> 00:00:17,050
Do you take digital payments?

3
00:00:17,130 --> 00:00:19,040
Sorry, we're cash only.

4
00:00:20,130 --> 00:00:21,740
- Oh, I see.
- Yes, sorry.

5
00:00:22,970 --> 00:00:25,970
As I prepare to set foot on a path
I never imagined taking,

6
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:28,380
I find myself

7
00:00:28,430 --> 00:00:30,370
feeling a little shaken.

8
00:00:33,150 --> 00:00:34,390
Thanks for coming.

9
00:00:34,720 --> 00:00:37,360
You saved me from
accidentally dining and dashing.

10
00:00:38,750 --> 00:00:40,840
Don't treat your employer
like your personal errand boy.

11
00:00:41,490 --> 00:00:42,490
Here.

12
00:00:43,500 --> 00:00:44,500
Candy?

13
00:00:45,210 --> 00:00:46,210
That's a first.

14
00:00:47,080 --> 00:00:49,800
I'm trying to quit smoking to save money.

15
00:00:50,820 --> 00:00:51,820
To save money?

16
00:00:52,930 --> 00:00:53,930
It's important, you know.

17
00:00:54,170 --> 00:00:55,170
Saving up...

18
00:00:59,830 --> 00:01:02,070
for tuition,

19
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:05,280
textbooks...

20
00:01:06,150 --> 00:01:08,450
And commuting costs
really start to add up.

21
00:01:11,360 --> 00:01:12,810
It all comes down to money.

22
00:01:14,160 --> 00:01:15,160
And then,

23
00:01:15,170 --> 00:01:16,630
of all times...

24
00:01:17,070 --> 00:01:19,440
Wait! Dad's coming back?

25
00:01:19,990 --> 00:01:21,570
Not until next spring,

26
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:23,990
but his time away is finally over.

27
00:01:24,550 --> 00:01:25,550
Are you serious?

28
00:01:26,190 --> 00:01:29,180
Honestly, it feels a little awkward
having him back now.

29
00:01:29,470 --> 00:01:32,340
Hey, don't say that.
Poor Dad.

30
00:01:32,780 --> 00:01:33,780
Yeah.

31
00:01:34,010 --> 00:01:36,680
You know, Sakutaro,
you're welcome to keep living here.

32
00:01:36,680 --> 00:01:37,880
We have the extra room anyway.

33
00:01:37,900 --> 00:01:40,200
- No, I couldn't impose like that.
- Exactly.

34
00:01:40,470 --> 00:01:41,990
Saku-chan, you're not allowed to move out.

35
00:01:42,110 --> 00:01:43,210
We have to stay together forever!

36
00:01:43,540 --> 00:01:44,890
Together forever, huh...

37
00:01:44,940 --> 00:01:47,410
Why don't you try saying that to your father?

38
00:01:58,120 --> 00:01:59,120
Sigh...

39
00:02:05,100 --> 00:02:09,100
(Incoming Call: Tajimi Yasuyuki)

40
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:50,300
"Life In Smokey Blue"

41
00:02:50,400 --> 00:02:54,100
(Episode 5: A New Step)

42
00:02:54,150 --> 00:02:55,780
Sorry to call you over like this
on such short notice.

43
00:03:00,020 --> 00:03:01,120
The thing is,

44
00:03:01,640 --> 00:03:04,970
I heard you quit your job as an MR.

45
00:03:05,220 --> 00:03:07,640
Oh, yes.

46
00:03:08,390 --> 00:03:11,440
I'm doing some translation work
for an acquaintance now.

47
00:03:12,160 --> 00:03:13,700
It's more of a freelance gig.

48
00:03:13,830 --> 00:03:15,430
- Translation?
- Yes.

49
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:18,250
I knew it.

50
00:03:18,340 --> 00:03:20,770
You always did have a gift for it.

51
00:03:21,260 --> 00:03:22,560
You're probably the only person

52
00:03:22,650 --> 00:03:24,040
who would ever say that to me, Tajimi-san.

53
00:03:24,510 --> 00:03:25,930
I still remember

54
00:03:26,250 --> 00:03:29,790
that Auster book you translated in class...

55
00:03:30,650 --> 00:03:32,310
- "Ghosts."
- That's it, "Ghosts."

56
00:03:32,310 --> 00:03:33,330
Paul Auster's "Ghosts."

57
00:03:42,420 --> 00:03:43,540
So, the reason I called...

58
00:03:44,740 --> 00:03:45,840
I have something I'd like to discuss.

59
00:03:48,250 --> 00:03:49,780
At the start of a new journey,

60
00:03:50,410 --> 00:03:52,370
unexpected paths begin to open up.

61
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:55,730
It's taking a shape

62
00:03:56,310 --> 00:03:57,550
that's slightly different from before.

63
00:03:58,530 --> 00:03:59,950
Bright...

64
00:04:00,760 --> 00:04:01,870
Clear.

65
00:04:03,370 --> 00:04:04,470
Weep...

66
00:04:06,070 --> 00:04:08,090
Shedding.

67
00:04:11,990 --> 00:04:13,810
This is from "Song of Spring"...

68
00:04:14,600 --> 00:04:15,600
How's the progress?

69
00:04:15,930 --> 00:04:17,130
You scared me!

70
00:04:18,480 --> 00:04:19,680
When did you get back?

71
00:04:19,830 --> 00:04:20,830
Just now.

72
00:04:22,340 --> 00:04:25,300
Oh. How did the meeting go?

73
00:04:25,370 --> 00:04:26,910
Fine. Same as usual.

74
00:04:27,930 --> 00:04:28,930
Here.

75
00:04:29,330 --> 00:04:30,530
A little something for you.

76
00:04:32,120 --> 00:04:34,550
The person I met with
happened to be a candy-giver.

77
00:04:35,910 --> 00:04:37,570
And you actually took some?

78
00:04:38,360 --> 00:04:41,000
I figured someone I know
usually carries candy around.

79
00:04:42,360 --> 00:04:44,330
You're so sweet, Shizuka-chan.

80
00:04:53,460 --> 00:04:55,020
You've made a lot of progress.

81
00:05:01,930 --> 00:05:02,930
Actually...

82
00:05:06,330 --> 00:05:07,330
Yeah?

83
00:05:09,240 --> 00:05:10,240
I...

84
00:05:11,040 --> 00:05:13,180
I'm going to work as a cram school teacher.

85
00:05:15,580 --> 00:05:16,780
A cram school teacher?

86
00:05:17,270 --> 00:05:18,270
Yeah.

87
00:05:19,840 --> 00:05:23,250
I did it part-time back in college.

88
00:05:25,940 --> 00:05:27,510
An upperclassman I worked with

89
00:05:27,960 --> 00:05:30,010
asked if I'd join him.

90
00:05:31,710 --> 00:05:32,710
Oh...

91
00:05:33,760 --> 00:05:34,940
Is this the one you mentioned before,

92
00:05:35,550 --> 00:05:37,210
the one who studied abroad?

93
00:05:37,750 --> 00:05:38,750
That's the one.

94
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:41,000
He's the one who praised my translation.

95
00:05:43,430 --> 00:05:44,860
He's always looked out for me,

96
00:05:45,420 --> 00:05:47,110
and he's been checking in on me lately.

97
00:05:49,320 --> 00:05:50,320
So,

98
00:05:52,460 --> 00:05:54,040
thinking about the future,

99
00:05:54,820 --> 00:05:57,580
I think it's best if I go help him out.

100
00:06:00,550 --> 00:06:01,550
I see.

101
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:07,200
Which means...

102
00:06:11,540 --> 00:06:12,760
regarding my work here with you,

103
00:06:14,560 --> 00:06:16,370
once I finish this glossary,

104
00:06:17,790 --> 00:06:19,000
I'd like to resign.

105
00:06:23,490 --> 00:06:24,880
I know it's sudden and selfish,

106
00:06:25,360 --> 00:06:26,460
and I'm really sorry.

107
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:30,900
I understand.

108
00:06:32,990 --> 00:06:34,880
I expect to be done by the end of the year.

109
00:06:37,030 --> 00:06:40,500
Okay, got it.

110
00:07:00,160 --> 00:07:01,670
Well, that was straightforward.

111
00:07:13,220 --> 00:07:14,440
It's tight...

112
00:07:15,447 --> 00:07:17,047
[Onboarding documentation for his new job]

113
00:07:17,610 --> 00:07:18,480
Oh.

114
00:07:18,480 --> 00:07:19,640
Azuma, let me introduce you.

115
00:07:19,640 --> 00:07:21,370
This is Ms. Shimada from the office.

116
00:07:21,500 --> 00:07:22,500
I'm Shimada. Nice to meet you.

117
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:23,620
I'm Azuma. Nice to meet you too.

118
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:25,120
I'll be in your care starting next month.

119
00:07:25,990 --> 00:07:26,990
Looking forward to it.

120
00:07:29,910 --> 00:07:30,910
Whoa.

121
00:07:33,290 --> 00:07:34,770
Are you serious?

122
00:08:00,260 --> 00:08:01,260
Yeah.

123
00:08:02,590 --> 00:08:03,790
The layout is very clear.

124
00:08:05,250 --> 00:08:06,350
It's finally finished.

125
00:08:12,960 --> 00:08:14,340
Thank goodness.

126
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:21,200
Well then...

127
00:08:21,350 --> 00:08:22,820
I should probably head out.

128
00:08:24,230 --> 00:08:25,230
Yeah.

129
00:08:52,280 --> 00:08:53,530
Winter thunder.

130
00:08:55,810 --> 00:08:57,050
You don't hear that often.

131
00:09:00,010 --> 00:09:01,010
Huh?

132
00:09:06,410 --> 00:09:07,510
The power's out.

133
00:09:08,800 --> 00:09:10,000
Is the data okay?

134
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:11,610
The data's fine, but...

135
00:09:13,900 --> 00:09:15,750
I can't do any more work today.

136
00:09:16,510 --> 00:09:17,510
And just so you know,

137
00:09:17,810 --> 00:09:19,060
my deadline is tomorrow morning.

138
00:09:19,750 --> 00:09:20,910
Oh...

139
00:09:22,380 --> 00:09:23,440
That's rare for you.

140
00:09:23,900 --> 00:09:25,290
You're usually so ahead of schedule.

141
00:09:27,110 --> 00:09:28,110
Ah.

142
00:09:28,790 --> 00:09:30,540
Does this have to do with
what happened in Yamanashi?

143
00:09:30,540 --> 00:09:31,780
That has nothing to do with this.

144
00:09:36,210 --> 00:09:37,210
Well,

145
00:09:37,860 --> 00:09:39,320
if you use your laptop...

146
00:09:39,410 --> 00:09:43,800
Sorry, I'm only at 3%.

147
00:09:45,520 --> 00:09:46,520
Oh.

148
00:09:50,840 --> 00:09:52,490
I guess we wait for the power.

149
00:09:54,250 --> 00:09:55,450
Not much else we can do.

150
00:09:57,480 --> 00:09:58,950
They're saying it's a major blackout.

151
00:09:59,600 --> 00:10:00,800
Even the trains have stopped.

152
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:04,920
I heard winter lightning
carries a much stronger current.

153
00:10:09,750 --> 00:10:10,850
Well, since we're stuck...

154
00:10:12,100 --> 00:10:13,200
Want to do something?

155
00:10:16,910 --> 00:10:19,140
In this freezing weather?
I can't believe you're in the mood.

156
00:10:19,140 --> 00:10:21,750
Huddling together might keep us warm.

157
00:10:37,670 --> 00:10:38,870
It's fine, go ahead and smoke.

158
00:10:39,540 --> 00:10:40,740
I thought you were quitting.

159
00:10:40,980 --> 00:10:42,080
It's not so much quitting

160
00:10:42,160 --> 00:10:44,210
as it is just saving the money.

161
00:10:45,660 --> 00:10:46,660
I see.

162
00:11:02,150 --> 00:11:03,150
Hey, Kuji.

163
00:11:05,060 --> 00:11:06,850
Why did you choose medical translation?

164
00:11:11,400 --> 00:11:12,720
Because there's a demand for it.

165
00:11:14,670 --> 00:11:15,870
That's it?

166
00:11:17,330 --> 00:11:19,510
I wanted to use my knowledge and skills

167
00:11:20,810 --> 00:11:22,500
to actually help people.

168
00:11:25,530 --> 00:11:26,530
It sounds cliché,

169
00:11:27,930 --> 00:11:29,280
but I really mean it.

170
00:11:33,130 --> 00:11:34,130
Yeah.

171
00:11:35,450 --> 00:11:36,450
I get that.

172
00:11:38,820 --> 00:11:40,750
This relationship without a name...

173
00:11:41,990 --> 00:11:43,090
is it ending today, too?

174
00:11:44,870 --> 00:11:45,870
Ah.

175
00:11:53,150 --> 00:11:54,720
The trains should be running again soon.

176
00:11:56,500 --> 00:11:57,710
Looks like you'll make the last train.

177
00:12:01,980 --> 00:12:03,460
That deadline tomorrow...

178
00:12:04,210 --> 00:12:05,410
is it for a book?

179
00:12:05,640 --> 00:12:06,840
Or is it medical?

180
00:12:10,010 --> 00:12:11,110
It's for a publisher.

181
00:12:11,720 --> 00:12:12,820
Then let me help.

182
00:12:13,990 --> 00:12:15,190
I'll make sure

183
00:12:15,900 --> 00:12:17,000
you hit your deadline.

184
00:12:18,700 --> 00:12:19,700
I have no idea what you're talking about.

185
00:12:20,260 --> 00:12:21,540
Let me be blunt then.

186
00:12:23,700 --> 00:12:26,600
I'm expecting some serious overtime pay.

187
00:12:40,170 --> 00:12:43,090
Three months have passed since I reunited
with my hated former colleague.

188
00:12:45,070 --> 00:12:46,170
It's been both stimulating

189
00:12:48,410 --> 00:12:49,560
and surprisingly comfortable.

190
00:12:52,040 --> 00:12:54,160
They were peaceful, steady days.

191
00:13:06,300 --> 00:13:08,380
Ah, all done.

192
00:13:10,200 --> 00:13:11,360
Good work.

193
00:13:24,490 --> 00:13:25,490
The sun's coming up.

194
00:13:32,010 --> 00:13:33,010
Are you hungry?

195
00:13:35,670 --> 00:13:36,670
Not really.

196
00:13:39,620 --> 00:13:40,620
More importantly,

197
00:13:40,800 --> 00:13:42,000
give me a cigarette.

198
00:13:44,080 --> 00:13:45,080
Huh?

199
00:13:45,130 --> 00:13:46,130
Here.

200
00:13:46,400 --> 00:13:47,400
Ah.

201
00:14:06,660 --> 00:14:08,060
If I leave right now,

202
00:14:08,650 --> 00:14:10,130
you'll be lonely, won't you?

203
00:14:12,400 --> 00:14:13,820
What are you even talking about?

204
00:14:21,610 --> 00:14:22,610
It's freezing.

205
00:14:30,040 --> 00:14:31,850
Have you ever seen the movie
"Blue in the Face"?

206
00:14:34,460 --> 00:14:35,460
Oh...

207
00:14:35,730 --> 00:14:37,200
That's the sequel to "Smoke," right?

208
00:14:38,070 --> 00:14:39,070
Yeah, I've seen it.

209
00:14:42,050 --> 00:14:43,850
There's this heavy smoker

210
00:14:44,550 --> 00:14:45,710
who decides to quit.

211
00:14:45,710 --> 00:14:49,710
There's a scene where he shares
one last cigarette with the protagonist.

212
00:14:54,600 --> 00:14:56,120
I always loved that scene.

213
00:15:03,550 --> 00:15:05,070
So, is this your last one?

214
00:15:07,280 --> 00:15:08,280
Who knows.

215
00:15:17,880 --> 00:15:20,000
After all the preparation,

216
00:15:20,890 --> 00:15:21,890
it's finally started.

217
00:15:22,090 --> 00:15:24,040
My life as a cram school teacher.

218
00:15:24,530 --> 00:15:27,760
Before the word "human,"

219
00:15:28,670 --> 00:15:29,890
there's actually a hidden "that" here.

220
00:15:30,110 --> 00:15:31,110
And then, this...

221
00:15:31,520 --> 00:15:32,520
Ah.

222
00:15:32,710 --> 00:15:33,630
Yeah.

223
00:15:33,630 --> 00:15:34,580
Can you reach it?

224
00:15:34,580 --> 00:15:34,980
Yeah.

225
00:15:35,020 --> 00:15:36,020
I think so.

226
00:15:41,410 --> 00:15:42,890
A place that once felt so foreign

227
00:15:43,010 --> 00:15:44,550
is slowly becoming familiar.

228
00:15:45,280 --> 00:15:45,910
Here you go.

229
00:15:46,010 --> 00:15:48,800
- Wait, there's dust on it.
- I said I was sorry.

230
00:15:48,800 --> 00:15:51,510
- No, no, stop!
- Let me just get it off.

231
00:15:57,699 --> 00:16:01,239
[Searching for properties in Tokyo with a
veranda with zero results]

232
00:16:08,460 --> 00:16:10,060
I really want a smoke.

233
00:16:18,800 --> 00:16:23,000
(Kuji Shizuka)

234
00:16:49,370 --> 00:16:51,160
This source text has a lot of personality.

235
00:17:15,820 --> 00:17:17,170
"Song of Spring."

236
00:17:17,730 --> 00:17:19,030
How would you translate this?

237
00:17:58,210 --> 00:17:59,210
Hey.

238
00:17:59,680 --> 00:18:00,680
I've been meaning to ask.

239
00:18:00,750 --> 00:18:03,160
Why don't you ever translate
words like "I" or "my"?

240
00:18:03,590 --> 00:18:04,840
You called me just to ask that?

241
00:18:05,340 --> 00:18:06,590
Well, usually,

242
00:18:06,950 --> 00:18:08,970
people would use "I" in the translation.

243
00:18:09,520 --> 00:18:10,660
But your draft doesn't have a single one.

244
00:18:10,660 --> 00:18:11,690
I was wondering why.

245
00:18:15,360 --> 00:18:19,060
Are you talking about "Song of Spring"?

246
00:18:19,570 --> 00:18:21,140
It's been bugging me.

247
00:18:21,140 --> 00:18:22,560
I can't stop thinking about it.

248
00:18:34,270 --> 00:18:35,370
I just felt like having "I" in there

249
00:18:35,450 --> 00:18:37,220
didn't feel right, no matter how I phrased it.

250
00:18:37,510 --> 00:18:39,360
So I decided to avoid the first person entirely.

251
00:18:40,190 --> 00:18:41,390
Does it sound unnatural?

252
00:18:41,670 --> 00:18:42,670
No.

253
00:18:42,780 --> 00:18:46,280
Then why did you translate "Bluebell"
as "little blue flower"?

254
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:48,450
I was prioritizing the flow of the rhythm.

255
00:18:49,350 --> 00:18:50,450
It is verse, after all.

256
00:18:59,940 --> 00:19:02,540
Do cram school teachers
have to do this kind of work too?

257
00:19:05,210 --> 00:19:06,210
Actually,

258
00:19:07,680 --> 00:19:10,090
I've decided to go to translation school.

259
00:19:14,140 --> 00:19:15,140
What?

260
00:19:16,610 --> 00:19:17,810
It's only once a week,

261
00:19:18,240 --> 00:19:19,810
but I wanted to give it a real shot.

262
00:19:20,120 --> 00:19:23,360
So I'm just going to try it.

263
00:19:26,580 --> 00:19:27,880
I see.

264
00:19:30,720 --> 00:19:32,800
Why do you look so happy about it?

265
00:19:33,310 --> 00:19:34,310
Huh?

266
00:19:34,460 --> 00:19:35,460
No,

267
00:19:36,340 --> 00:19:37,410
well...

268
00:19:38,490 --> 00:19:41,010
It is pretty strange, isn't it?

269
00:19:41,790 --> 00:19:42,790
It's very strange.

270
00:19:52,070 --> 00:19:53,370
Want to go get some curry udon?

271
00:20:11,650 --> 00:20:13,340
Give me one of those.

272
00:20:18,240 --> 00:20:20,020
I thought you were quitting.

273
00:20:21,500 --> 00:20:24,460
I told you, I'm not quitting.

274
00:20:24,960 --> 00:20:27,480
I'm just trying to save money.

275
00:20:29,740 --> 00:20:30,840
That attitude of yours

276
00:20:31,470 --> 00:20:33,030
is the absolute worst.

277
00:20:34,740 --> 00:20:36,330
Between school and everything,

278
00:20:36,980 --> 00:20:39,630
I'm also looking for a new place.

279
00:20:42,110 --> 00:20:43,520
Are you moving out of your sister's?

280
00:20:44,880 --> 00:20:47,660
My brother-in-law is coming back.

281
00:20:48,790 --> 00:20:52,380
I can't just stay there and be in the way.

282
00:20:54,720 --> 00:20:55,720
I see.

283
00:20:58,060 --> 00:20:59,060
But honestly,

284
00:20:59,780 --> 00:21:01,240
it's going to be tough.

285
00:21:02,360 --> 00:21:04,050
I have some savings,

286
00:21:04,720 --> 00:21:07,230
but moving is so expensive.

287
00:21:13,010 --> 00:21:14,010
In that case,

288
00:21:15,550 --> 00:21:16,650
why don't you just stay at my place?

289
00:21:19,070 --> 00:21:20,070
Wait, what?

290
00:21:22,520 --> 00:21:23,520
What?

291
00:21:23,740 --> 00:21:24,840
I mean,

292
00:21:25,600 --> 00:21:27,320
it wouldn't be for long.

293
00:21:28,950 --> 00:21:30,660
Until you find your next place,

294
00:21:31,400 --> 00:21:32,900
you can use the spare room.

295
00:21:37,070 --> 00:21:38,070
Are you serious?

296
00:21:40,890 --> 00:21:42,850
You're out during the day anyway.

297
00:21:44,750 --> 00:21:46,320
And if you want to study translation,

298
00:21:46,910 --> 00:21:48,780
I have plenty of reference books.

299
00:21:50,350 --> 00:21:51,350
Well,

300
00:21:52,820 --> 00:21:54,420
if you don't mind...

301
00:22:09,610 --> 00:22:10,900
I'll be in your care, then.

302
00:22:14,220 --> 00:22:15,420
You're being dramatic.

303
00:22:18,860 --> 00:22:19,860
Um...

304
00:22:20,380 --> 00:22:21,580
Kuji-san?

305
00:22:25,890 --> 00:22:26,890
What?

306
00:22:27,800 --> 00:22:28,900
The curry udon.

307
00:22:29,510 --> 00:22:30,610
Is it ready yet?

308
00:22:36,960 --> 00:22:38,060
Alright, alright.

309
00:22:42,690 --> 00:22:43,690
Let me help.

310
00:22:46,920 --> 00:22:48,020
Stop it.

311
00:22:49,680 --> 00:22:51,770
Cut it out. Get away from me.

312
00:22:51,980 --> 00:22:53,320
No matter the weather,

313
00:22:54,140 --> 00:22:55,550
being in this house

314
00:22:55,750 --> 00:22:56,810
doesn't seem so bad.

315
00:23:00,480 --> 00:23:01,810
(Next Episode)
At this age,

316
00:23:01,870 --> 00:23:03,440
I'm actually chasing a dream.

317
00:23:03,640 --> 00:23:04,610
I'm home.

318
00:23:04,610 --> 00:23:05,810
Go wash your hands.

319
00:23:05,880 --> 00:23:07,330
Is your brother moving in in May?

320
00:23:07,330 --> 00:23:08,840
You didn't say a word about this.

321
00:23:08,920 --> 00:23:10,290
Get up. Let's go home.

322
00:23:10,290 --> 00:23:14,410
That house really suits you.
